    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Asking about Daily Habits"
        },
        "text": "To ask someone 'What do you do every day?', you use: شو بتعمل (shoo bte'mal) for a male, and شو بتعملي (shoo bte'mali) for a female, followed by كل يوم (kull yōm - every day).",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "شو بتعملَ كل يوم الصبح؟",
            "english": "What do you do every morning? (to male)",
            "transliteration": "Shoo bte'mal kull yōm iṣ-ṣubḥ?"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "شو بتعملِ كل يوم المسا؟",
            "english": "What do you do every evening? (to female)",
            "transliteration": "Shoo bte'mali kull yōm il-masa?"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Time Expressions: Morning, Afternoon, Evening"
        },
        "text": "Here are common phrases to specify parts of the day in Levantine Arabic.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "أنا بشتغل الصبح.",
            "english": "I work in the morning.",
            "transliteration": "Ana bashtaghil iṣ-ṣubḥ."
          },
          {
            "arabic": "هو بروح ع النادي بعد الظهر.",
            "english": "He goes to the gym in the afternoon.",
            "transliteration": "Huwa barooḥ a'n-naadi ba'd iḍ-ḍuhr."
          },
          {
            "arabic": "نحنا بنطلع المسا.",
            "english": "We go out in the evening.",
            "transliteration": "Niḥna binṭla' il-masa."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
